{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9cc1f139-6363-4086-96d6-f002036ab994","content":"## CPU Baseline Requirement Change\n\nStarting with **.NET 10**, Microsoft raised the minimum x86-64 CPU baseline from **x86-64-v1** to **x86-64-v2**. This carries forward into .NET 11. The v2 baseline requires:\n\n| Instruction Set | Typical Support |\n|---|---|\n| SSE3, SSSE3 | Most CPUs since ~2006 |\n| SSE4.1, SSE4.2 | Intel Penryn/Nehalem (2008+), AMD Bulldozer (2011+) |\n| POPCNT | Intel Nehalem (2008+), AMD Barcelona (2007+) |\n| CMPXCHG16B | Most 64-bit CPUs, but some early AMD K8 lack it |\n\nYour **2012-era node** likely has a CPU that's missing one of these (common culprits: older AMD chips lacking SSSE3 or SSE4.2).\n\n**Diagnose it** by running on the failing node:\n\n```bash\ngrep -E 'ssse3|sse4_1|sse4_2|popcnt|cx16' /proc/cpuinfo | head -1\n```\n\n**Your other platforms are fine:**\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1):** Arm64 has its own baseline; unaffected.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Arm64/Armv8):** Also unaffected by x86 baseline changes.\n\n**Options to resolve:**\n1. **Replace the old hardware** — simplest long-term fix.\n2. **Pin those nodes to .NET 9** — last version with v1 baseline.\n3. **Build a custom runtime** from source with v1 baseline (unsupported, not recommended).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d77d4576-e0ff-4e1f-b4c0-7ad6d3c650b7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 10 (and continuing in .NET 11), Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. Hardware from 2012 might not support all of these instructions.\n\n\nLet me double-check the timeline here—the x86-64-v2 baseline was announced for .NET 10, so if they were already running .NET 10 without issues, this error shouldn't suddenly appear in .NET 11 unless the requirement was tightened further or they weren't actually hitting this constraint before. The fact that one Linux x86 node is failing suggests it might be a hardware-specific issue on that particular machine rather than a blanket change between versions. The x86-64-v2 baseline was likely introduced in .NET 10, so the user's ability to run .NET 10 on 2012 hardware is puzzling if that's the case. Either .NET 10 only warned without enforcing the requirement, or the baseline was actually raised in .NET 11, or the user's hardware happened to support v2 despite its age. set requirements. Starting with a certain .NET version, the runtime now requires x86-64-v2 instructions (SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, CMPXCHG16B, LAHF/SAHF), and some CPUs from 2012—particularly certain AMD processors—don't support all of these. The other platforms like Windows Arm64 and Raspberry Pi should be fine since .NET has solid Arm support. The real solution is either upgrading that hardware, staying on an older .NET version for those nodes, or identifying exactly which CPU is failing and what instructions it's missing.","outputTokens":1565,"requestId":"4011:1E7C59:15AC081:1882456:69F94B1A"},"id":"3336141d-6fb4-4524-ab0c-fa2056764af7","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:43:24.010Z","parentId":"04309f9d-17b1-41f9-af7a-57c7792c5ab0"}
